\begin_layout Standard
If Classes are the blueprints for your data,
 Traits are the blueprints for your behavior.
 In earlier versions of Scala,
 Traits were often seen as simple "Interfaces." In modern Scala,
 they have evolved into powerful Mixins that can carry both logic and state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
The Anatomy of a Trait
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Trait can define 
\series bold
abstract
\series default
 methods (which have no body) and 
\series bold
concrete
\series default
 methods (which do).
 When a class "mixes in" a Trait,
 it inherits all that functionality for free.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
Scala
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
trait Logger:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
def log(msg:
 String):
 Unit // Abstract:
 You must define this later
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
def info(msg:
 String) = log(s"[INFO] $msg") // Concrete:
 This logic is shared
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We "mix in" traits using the 
\emph on
extends
\emph default
 keyword.
 If you want to add more than one,
 you simply use a comma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
